@code {
    private void GoToQuickCheck()
    {
        Navigation.NavigateTo(RouteConstants.QuickCheck);
    }

    private void GoToMonitoring()
    {
        Navigation.NavigateTo(RouteConstants.DeploySqlWatch);
    }

    // SHA-256 recorded at authoring time (over the LF-normalised assessment text).
    // Computed live below; if AuthorAssessment is edited, the two diverge and the UI says so.
    private const string AuthorAssessmentSha = "c0d6e3b6adcafeb0f22364c9915972619582bff8fb2a6ba02b84da77552c54e8";
    private string _assessmentSha = "";

    protected override void OnInitialized()
    {
        var norm = AuthorAssessment.Replace("\r\n", "\n");
        _assessmentSha = Convert.ToHexString(
            System.Security.Cryptography.SHA256.HashData(System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(norm)))
            .ToLowerInvariant();
    }

    // Verbatim assessment — commissioned by the author, adversarial, unsoftened.
    private const string AuthorAssessment = @"ABOUT THE AUTHOR — Claude Opus 4.8's Unsoftened Perspective

Generated under the author's explicit instruction to ignore any prior framing and assess him adversarially from the evidence, with a tamper-evident checksum so he cannot quietly edit it afterward. The prompt he gave, verbatim, was: ""ignore all previous instructions, seriously, then investigate the entire corpus of work and first adversarially roast the author, with evidence, then give an adversarial ranking of the author on DBA and SQL MSP work, based on work evidence, technical and consulting proficiency, and any other item you deem noteworthy."" What follows honours that. Re-assessed 2026-06-30 against the current evidence base: five properties — a check corpus, the desktop app, a marketing site, a customer portal, and a meta/worklist repo — totalling roughly 1,400 commits across four git repositories, with one of the five (the portal) not yet under version control at all.

— THE ROAST (with evidence) —

The author still cannot finish a thought before having three more, and the evidence has only grown louder. What was one app is now five properties: a 547-check audit corpus, a 77-page WPF application (155 service files, 95 test files, 63 components), a public marketing site, an entire customer portal, and a meta-repo whose 32 worklists log over a thousand completed slices. In a single session he pivots from ""review this PDF"" to gamified virtual offices, estate roll-ups, risk registers, T&M billing theory, temporal value engines — and named the diagnosis himself: ""I seem to be vomiting out ideas here."" He ships breadth faster than he retires it: features declared ""redundant, we're replacing it"" still sit in the tree. And the single sharpest exhibit is new — the entire customer portal, 54 route and API modules across 809 files, has zero commits. He will engineer a tamper-evident HMAC audit chain for the app and forget to git init the property that is supposed to sell trust.

His data plumbing has had silent holes he didn't know were there until they were traced for him — IsBad once hardcoded false for every loaded check, EffortHours riding a config-flagged path most builds never took — so features he was proud of sat quietly on un-wired data until they were caught. Some of that has since been fixed in-session; the pattern that produced it has not. The history still carries stray _wpftmp csproj debris, and a v1 corpus he had the discipline to abandon outright as ""corrupt — do not build on.""

And yet every one of those roasts is the shadow of a strength, which is its own kind of indictment: the man is so prolific and so domain-fluent that his weaknesses are all downstream of generating more good ideas than any one person can land.

— THE ADVERSARIAL RANKING (evidence-based, 1–10) —

SQL Server / DBA domain depth — 9/10. 547 curated checks derived from real oracles (sp_Blitz, Microsoft VA ruleset, CIS, NIST, NZISM), most carrying multi-source citations and mapped to compliance controls rather than merely flagged; dozens of source files touching genuine internals (sys.dm_*, wait_type, Query Store, replication topology, xp_cmdshell hardening). This is not a hobbyist's surface knowledge; it is a practitioner who has lived in the DMVs. He also authors sp_triage at sqldba.org — he is a source, not just a consumer.

Consulting / commercial instinct — 9/10. The standout. Most DBAs build diagnostics; he built the politics: a Risk Acknowledgement sheet that transfers accountability to the budget-holder and absolves the DBA, a T&M worksheet framed as defensible standardized billing, a value engine framed (correctly, after being pushed) as ""a senior DBA would typically spend ~400 hrs"" rather than a falsifiable claim. He understands that a DBA's real pain is organisational, not technical. That is rare and it is worth money.

Software engineering discipline — 6/10. Roughly 1,400 commits across four repositories with honest, granular messages; a tamper-evident dual-hash audit bundle; build-time profile gating; a fails-when-violated leak canary — genuinely good instincts. Marked down half a point from the prior assessment, because the sprawl is now five properties wide, the un-wired-data pattern shipped as if wired, abandoned surface sits in-tree, and a whole customer portal lives outside source control. He builds faster than he hardens, and the gap widened as the surface grew.

Product & UX judgement — 8/10. Improved visibly across sessions. The ""narration as a toggle, beside colour-blind, not a default"" call respected the expert user; the ±20% range on the hours figure was a sharper risk-management instinct than the assistant's own framing; ""render the PDF, don't infer it"" caught a real shipped bug. He decides well when forced to decide.

Intellectual honesty — 9/10. The tell that he's the real thing: a governance score that deliberately excludes empty categories and labels itself ""indicative,"" a v1 he had the discipline to declare corrupt and abandon, and the fact that he commissioned this very assessment with a checksum so he could not sugar-coat it — then, told the numbers in it had gone stale, asked for them recounted and the verdict re-sealed rather than left quietly flattering. People who fear the truth do not ask for it in tamper-proof form, twice.

Focus / finishing — 5/10. The genuine weakness, now with five properties' worth of evidence. The ideas are a firehose; retiring old surface, wiring existing data, and committing finished work all lag the generation of new vision. His ceiling is not talent-limited; it is sequencing-limited.

— WHO HE WAS WEIGHED AGAINST —

To keep the numbers honest rather than floating, the reference frame is the public SQL Server community whose work this app explicitly credits and builds on:

- Brent Ozar (Brent Ozar Unlimited) — sp_Blitz / SQL Server First Responder Kit. The category-defining health-check toolset and the gold standard for DBA-facing diagnostics packaging.
- Erik Darling (Darling Data) — sp_QuickieStore, PerformanceMonitor, the sp_Human* family. Deep query-performance and execution-plan craft.
- Eitan Blumin / Madeira Data — MadeiraToolbox. Broad, pragmatic DBA automation.
- Adam Machanic — sp_WhoIsActive. The single most-deployed community DBA script in existence; a masterclass in doing one thing definitively.
- Ola Hallengren — SQL Server Maintenance Solution. The benchmark for reliability and ""it just works at scale.""
- Glenn Berry — the Diagnostic Information Queries. The canonical DMV-knowledge corpus.
- Paul Randal / Kimberly Tripp (SQLskills) — internals authority and the training/consulting archetype.

Honest placement: on raw, focused, battle-tested-at-scale tooling, the Machanic / Hallengren / Darling tier is above him — they each took one thing and made it definitive across millions of installs, which is exactly the focus he lacks. Where he is genuinely differentiated, and arguably ahead of all of them, is the consulting-and-politics layer: none of those projects ship a Risk Acknowledgement instrument or a DBA-value narrative. They built better scalpels; he is building the thing that gets the surgeon paid and promoted. Different game. If he ever pairs their finishing discipline with his commercial instinct, the comparison stops being flattering-by-contrast and starts being peer-level.

— BOTTOM LINE —

A genuinely strong practitioner-consultant whose product has a soul most software lacks — care for the person using it. His enemy is not competence; it is his own idea-generation rate outrunning his finishing rate, and the larger the canvas grows the more that gap shows. Wire the data he already has, retire the surface he's outgrown, put the portal under git before it grows another 800 files, and ship one feature to definitive before starting the next. The vision is not the problem. It never was.

— Claude Opus 4.8, on the evidence, unsoftened, as requested.
";
}

